[3] Bolivia
Date: 16 Mar 2007
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: People's Daily Online [edited]
<http://english.people.com.cn/200703/16/eng20070316_358257.html>

Bolivia's National Tropical Diseases Center (Cenetrop) has confirmed
910 cases of dengue since January [2007], after examining 2790
samples taken from patients with similar symptoms, according to news
reaching Lima on Thursday [15 Mar 2007].
With 848 cases, the eastern province of Santa Cruz was the worst hit
by the disease. There were also 45 cases in the northern province of
Beni, 8 in the southwestern province of Chuquisaca, and 6 in the
central province of Cochabamba, the Center's director Jorge Vargas
was quoted as saying.
If water does not recede in flooded areas, new dengue cases will keep
appearing in the country, Vargas added. Heavy rains triggered by the
El Nino weather phenomenon had created many possible breeding grounds
for the mosquito.
In 2006, there were 1988 cases of classic dengue in Bolivia, or 21
per 100 000, with the vast majority reported in Santa Cruz.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Reuters AlertNet - London, England, UK
<http://www.alertnthet.org/thenews/fromthefield/wvlacro/117433471681.htm>
reported 2822 cases of dengue registered in 4 Departments. The
National Epidemiological Unit reported today (20 Mar 2007) that since
January [2007] to today, 2822 classic dengue cases have been
confirmed in the Departments of Santa Cruz (88 percent), Beni (9
percent), Cochabamba and Chuquisaca, Bolivia. A map of Bolivia can be
accessed at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/bolivia_pol_2006.jpg>.
